 in 1876 to the death and cremation of Jerry Garcia in the late twentieth century. From the Gilded Age to the Progressive Era to the baby boomers of today, this book takes us on a tour through American culture and traces our changing attitudes toward death, religion, public health, the body, and the environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCremationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aCremationzUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 0aFuneral rites and ceremonieszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  a1800s.  a1900s.  a20th century.  aafterlife.  aamerican culture.  aamerican history.  acremation.  acultural anthropology.  acultural history.  acultural studies.  adeath.  aenvironmental.  afire.  afuneral rites.  afuneral.  afunereal.  agilded age.  ahistorical.  ahuman body.  alife and death.  amagazines.  amortician.  aprivate life.  aprogressive era.  apublic health.  apublic life.  areaders digest.  areligion.  asocial change.  asocial history.  asocial studies.  atransformation.  atrue story.  aunited states history.  aus history.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052020816240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092974640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520929746423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520929746/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY